Technological determinism is a concept that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, from the technological incentive or technological imperative to the strict understanding that the human concept of fate is guided by the basic logic associated with scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: that the very development of technology follows a path that is far beyond cultural or political influence, and that technology has “effects” on societies that are inherent, not social.
For example, it can be said that the invention of the car necessarily leads to the development of roads.
However, the road network across the country is not worth it for just a few cars, so new production methods have been developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
Mass ownership of cars leads to more accidents on the roads, leading to the discovery of new techniques in medical care to treat injuries.
